[{"id":27732,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Chemical Bonding and Molecular Structure","question":"","options":["Both Statement I and Statement II are false","Statement I is false but Statement II is true","Statement I is true but Statement II is false","Both Statement I and Statement II are true"],"answer":2,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/H59FLJLTc8Ar1N-s0tHlyIYoXlEEbnYptZcQ0LP6s5k.original.fullsize.png\"><br>\nBond length $\\propto \\frac{1}{\\text { Bond order }}$\nOrder of $\\mathrm{O}-\\mathrm{O}$ bond length\n$\\mathrm{O}=\\mathrm{O} < \\mathrm{O}_3 < \\mathrm{O}-\\mathrm{O}$\n$\\therefore$ Statement $I$ is true.\nLone pair-lone pair repulsion between O-atoms is not solely responsible for the correct order of O-O bond length. Bond order also should be considered.\n$\\therefore \\quad$ Statement II is false.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (24 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":27784,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Chemical Bonding and Molecular Structure","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>Paramagnetic molecules are those molecules in which unpaired electrons are present, while diamagnetic molecules are those in which unpaired electrons are absent.</p><p>The diatomic species with an odd number of electrons and those diatomic species that contain 10 or 16 electrons are paramagnetic. Among the given species <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msubsup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>2</mn><mo>+</mo></msubsup><mo>(</mo><mn>15</mn><mo>)</mo></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>B</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>(</mo><mn>10</mn><mo>)</mo></math> are paramgnetic species.<br/>The molecular orbital electronic configuration of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math> is.</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>:</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">σ</mi><mn>1</mn><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>,</mo><mo> </mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">σ</mi><mo>*</mo></msup><mn>1</mn><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>,</mo><mo> </mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">σ</mi><mn>2</mn><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>,</mo><mo> </mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">σ</mi><mo>*</mo></msup><mn>2</mn><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>,</mo><mo> </mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">π</mi><mn>2</mn><msubsup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">p</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">x</mi><mn>1</mn></msubsup><mo>,</mo><mo> </mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">π</mi><mn>2</mn><msubsup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">p</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">y</mi><mn>1</mn></msubsup></math></p><p>Bond order<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>Bonding</mi><mo> </mo><mi>electrons</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>antibonding</mi><mo> </mo><mi>electrons</mi></mrow><mn>2</mn></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>6</mn><mo>-</mo><mn>4</mn></mrow><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>2</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></math></p><p>Hence. the answer is <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (29 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":27811,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Chemical Bonding and Molecular Structure","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>IV</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>III</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>II</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>II</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>III</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>IV</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>IV</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>II</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>III</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>II</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>IV</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>III</mi></math>"],"answer":3,"solution":"<p>(A)&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>XeF</mi><mn>4</mn></msub></math>:</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/78c82e7e-8f33-4781-9922-58eb3f2e78f5-9896051.png\" style=\"width: 250px; height: 206px;\" /></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Xe</mi></math> has 4 bond pairs along with 2 lone pairs in the <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>XeF</mi><mn>4</mn></msub></math>.&nbsp;Thus, the hybridisation of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Xe</mi></math> is&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>sp</mi><mn>3</mn></msup><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></math>.&nbsp;Now since it contains two lone pairs it will show square planar geometry.</p><p>(B)&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>SF</mi><mn>4</mn></msub></math>:</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/aa69df98-c776-4ae4-b750-7f0a68dd0903-9896051_2.png\" style=\"width: 250px; height: 268px;\" /></p><p>The lone pair is an&nbsp;equatorial position, and there are two lone-pair&mdash;bond pair&nbsp;repulsions. Hence, it is more stable. So, the shape is described as a distorted tetrahedron, a folded square or a see-saw.</p><p>(C) <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msubsup><mi>NH</mi><mn>4</mn><mo>+</mo></msubsup></math>:</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/2e11c907-c11d-4afd-95d8-1365b323d5ce-9896051_3.png\" style=\"width: 300px; height: 185px;\" /></p><p>In&nbsp;this case steric&nbsp;number = lone pair + sigma bond = 0 + 4 = 4.&nbsp;</p><p>So, it is sp<sup>3</sup>&nbsp;hybridisation. There is no lone pair present. Thus, the shape of&nbsp;this ion is tetrahedral.</p><p>(D)&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>BrF</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math>:</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/00f9ad0e-e6f1-4f5c-97cb-01f191446316-9896051_4.png\" style=\"width: 250px; height: 229px;\" /></p><p>To decrease repulsion between the lone pairs, the molecule&#39;s structure is bent, making it T-shaped.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (31 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":27783,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Chemical Bonding and Molecular Structure","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>A pair of electrons which is not shared by any of the reacting atoms is called a lone pair of electrons. <strong>Lone pairs </strong>are found in the outermost <strong>electron</strong> shell of atoms. They can be identified by using a Lewis structure.</p><p>The structures of the compounds are as follows,</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/f29e5d8f-51e9-409e-93bc-3556961a3879.png\" style=\"width: 400px; height: 441px;\"/></p><p>Hence the compounds <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>NH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><msub><mi>SF</mi><mn>4</mn></msub><mo> </mo><mi>and</mi><mo> </mo><msub><mi>BrF</mi><mn>5</mn></msub></math> have one lone pair on central metal atom.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (29 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":27973,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Chemical Bonding and Molecular Structure","question":"","options":["<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/vEE-pm2lnrHrZAHunTz0yBe4D-6lh2rBuiPIwIP8gz4.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/Sef72JqQ-rdyee6oqa_7WmUq7v65mXNJwtRyZiZes9U.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/HmWRrnnVWNbi49qO42UBPdcKxe779nEzz0ErjeudacA.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/SpDdNf3JzOTBLv7VJqUQsbL3_kdjhJTXuRKF-M94-F0.original.fullsize.png\"><br>"],"answer":2,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/GKF3eWScX0pp0PQhSatChE_M0jer3lM1uTe8KjryO-k.original.fullsize.png\"><br>\nDipole moment $(\\mu)=0$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2012 (12 May Online)","image":null},{"id":27734,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Chemical Bonding and Molecular Structure","question":"","options":["4 and 5","3 and 5","3 and 6","4 and 6"],"answer":1,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/KN-1uYCREH9LU3TOdQzrybG2t9O0L-b3ti6GtLNE1CA.original.fullsize.png\"><br>\n\nNumber of sp and $\\mathrm{sp}^2$ hybridised carbon atom are 3 and 5.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (24 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":27927,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Chemical Bonding and Molecular Structure","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>33</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>and</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>25</mn></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>67</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>and</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>75</mn></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>50</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>and</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>75</mn></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>33</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>and</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>75</mn></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<table border=\"1\">\t<tbody>\t\t<tr>\t\t\t<td>Graphite</td>\t\t\t<td>Diamond</td>\t\t</tr>\t\t<tr>\t\t\t<td><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>sp</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></math> hybridisation</td>\t\t\t<td><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>sp</mi><mn>3</mn></msup></math> hybridisation</td>\t\t</tr>\t\t<tr>\t\t\t<td><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>%&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>2</mn><mn>3</mn></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>100</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>67</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">%</mi></math></td>\t\t\t<td><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>%&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>3</mn><mn>4</mn></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>100</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>75</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">%</mi></math></td>\t\t</tr>\t\t<tr>\t\t\t<td>For <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>sp</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></math>: <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>%</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi></math> character<br />\t\t\t<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi><mo>&#8722;</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mi>cos&#952;</mi></math><br />\t\t\t<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi><mo>&#8722;</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mi>cos</mi><mn>120</mn><mo>=</mo><mo>&#8722;</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.5</mo></math><br />\t\t\t<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi><mo>&#8722;</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.5</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi></math><br />\t\t\t<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn><mo>.5</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></math><br />\t\t\t<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>2</mn><mn>3</mn></mfrac></math><br />\t\t\t<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">%</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>2</mn><mn>3</mn></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>100</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>66</mn><mo>.67</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">%</mi></math></td>\t\t\t<td>For <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>sp</mi><mn>3</mn></msup></math>: <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>%</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi></math> character<br />\t\t\t<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi><mo>&#8722;</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mi>cos</mi><mn>109</mn><mo>'</mo><mn>28</mn></math><br />\t\t\t<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi><mo>&#8722;</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.33</mo></math><br />\t\t\t<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi><mo>&#8722;</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>3</mn><mn>4</mn></mfrac></math><br />\t\t\t<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">%</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">P</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>75</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">%</mi></math></td>\t\t</tr>\t</tbody></table>&nbsp;<br />&nbsp;","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2018 (15 Apr)","image":null},{"id":27847,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Chemical Bonding and Molecular Structure","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>Electrons which are not involved in the bond formation are called the lone pair of electrons.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/05f2d852-c245-41ad-9f1f-ada45b5d0893-image.png\" style=\"width: 300px; height: 274px;\" /></p><p>As we can see from the structures&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>XeF</mi><mn>4</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></math>&nbsp;are having two lone pairs on the central atom.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (26 Jun Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":27727,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Chemical Bonding and Molecular Structure","question":"","options":["3 and 13","11 and 3","13 and 3","14 and 3"],"answer":2,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/qlRVv50y3auwRwZhq7dBBQqkJzceVhM-nG_DtvQLkWo.original.fullsize.png\"><br>\n\n\n\n\n$\\begin{aligned} \\sigma \\text { bonds } & =13 \\\\ \\pi \\text { bonds } & =3\\end{aligned}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (29 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":27729,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Chemical Bonding and Molecular Structure","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/igFTuwOS9UyU4Z48k5GsSSVC7koyHAcupRh_79CLM5Y.original.fullsize.png\"><br>\n\n\nNumber of $\\sigma$ bond $=11$\nNumber of $\\pi$ bond $=4$\n$\\sigma+\\pi=11+4=15$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (29 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":27738,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Chemical Bonding and Molecular Structure","question":"","options":["$\\mathrm{H}_2 \\mathrm{~S} \\lt \\mathrm{HBr} \\lt \\mathrm{NF}_3 \\lt \\mathrm{CHCl}_3$","$\\mathrm{NF}_3 \\lt \\mathrm{HBr} \\lt \\mathrm{H}_2 \\mathrm{~S} \\lt \\mathrm{CHCl}_3$","$\\mathrm{HBr} \\lt \\mathrm{H}_2 \\mathrm{~S} \\lt \\mathrm{NF}_3 \\lt \\mathrm{CHCl}_3$","$\\mathrm{CHCl}_3 \\lt \\mathrm{NF}_3 \\lt \\mathrm{HBr} \\lt \\mathrm{H}_2 \\mathrm{~S}$"],"answer":1,"solution":"$\\begin{aligned}\n& \\mu_{\\mathrm{HBr}}=0.78 \\mathrm{D} \\\\\n& \\mu_{\\mathrm{H}_2 \\mathrm{~S}}=0.95 \\mathrm{D} \\\\\n& \\mu_{\\mathrm{NF}_3}=0.24 \\mathrm{D} \\\\\n& \\mu_{\\mathrm{CHCl}_3}=1.01 \\mathrm{D}\n\\end{aligned}$\n\nHence dipole moment of\n$\\mathrm{NF}_3 < \\mathrm{HBr} < \\mathrm{H}_2 \\mathrm{~S} < \\mathrm{CHCl}_3$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (22 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":27930,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Chemical Bonding and Molecular Structure","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>KCl</mi><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#160;</mi><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>6</mn></msub></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>KCl</mi><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#160;</mi><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>6</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#160;</mi><msub><mi>PH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>KCl</mi><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#160;</mi><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>SO</mi><mn>4</mn></msub></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>KCl</mi></math>"],"answer":3,"solution":"<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced close=\"}\" open=\"\" separators=\"|\"><mtable><mtr><mtd><msub><mi>PH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mtable><mtr><mtd><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>6</mn></msub></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>SO</mi><mn>4</mn></msub></mtd></mtr></mtable></mtd></mtr></mtable></mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#160;</mi><mi>All</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#160;</mi><mi>are</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#160;</mi><mi>covalent</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#160;</mi><mi>compounds</mi></math><br /><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>KCl</mi></math> is&nbsp;an ionic compound.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2018 (08 Apr)","image":null},{"id":27850,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Chemical Bonding and Molecular Structure","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></mfenced><mo>,</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></mfenced><mo>,</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></mfenced></math>&nbsp;only","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></mfenced><mo>,</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></mfenced><mo>,</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">E</mi></mfenced></math>&nbsp;only","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></mfenced><mo>,</mo><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">C</mi></mfenced></math>&nbsp;only","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">D</mi></mfenced></math>&nbsp;only"],"answer":2,"solution":"<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">In all these molecules&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>&#8203;</mo></mrow></msub><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>and</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>NO</mi></math>, is stabilized by removal of electrons because it is having electrons in the anti-bonding orbital. And thus removal of electron from the anti bonding orbital, increases the bond order of&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>and</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>NO</mi></math>​. And thus is becomes more stable after removal of electrons. Bond order of&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msubsup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>2</mn><mo>+</mo></msubsup><mo>&#8203;</mo></math>is <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn></math>&nbsp;and it is more&nbsp;than that of&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math>​&nbsp;which is having bond order as <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn></math>. Similarly Bond order of&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>NO</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>is</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>and</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>that</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>of</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mi>NO</mi><mo>+</mo></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>is</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>3</mn></math>.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (25 Jun Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":27846,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Chemical Bonding and Molecular Structure","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mrow/></msub></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>NO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>5</mn></msub></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p>Structures of the given oxides of nitrogen are as follows:</p><p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/6112accf-3576-4376-b263-02c9220b0669-d629cb99-09be-46f1-98cd-8fe12f4935dc-7.png\" style=\"width: 292px; height: 433px;\" /></p><p>As we can see only&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>NO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math>&nbsp;is having an odd electron on the nitrogen atom.It is the correct answer.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (26 Jun Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":27776,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Chemical Bonding and Molecular Structure","question":"","options":["Statement I is true but Statement II is false.","Both Statement I and Statement II are false.","Both statement I and Statement II is are true.","Statement I is false but Statement II is are true."],"answer":1,"solution":"<blockquote><p>The lone pair of nitrogen opposes the dipole moment of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>NF</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math> while it is added to the dipole moment of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>NH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math><br/>In <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>NH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math></p><p>Hydrogen is less electronegative than nitrogen, so all the electrons will move towards nitrogen. Due to this, all the vectors will be in the same direction and the summation will come to maximum.</p><p>In <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>NF</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math></p><p>Fluorine is more electronegative than nitrogen, so all the electrons will move towards fluorine. Due to this, all the vectors will cancel each other and the summation will come to a minimum.</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/e4addec3-8f50-4244-9265-ba0e88c32e8f.png\" style=\"width: 400px; height: 175px;\"/></p><p>In <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>NH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math>, the dipole moment vector of the bond and the lone pairs are in the same direction. But in <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>NF</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math>, the dipole moment vector of lone pairs and bond pairs are opposite in direction. So, the net dipole moment will be the subtractive effect of the two. Hence, the dipole moment of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>NH</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math> is larger than <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>NF</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math>.</p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (30 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":27743,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Chemical Bonding and Molecular Structure","question":"","options":["\\(\\mathrm{H}_2 \\mathrm{O}\\) and \\(\\mathrm{NO}_2\\)","\\(\\mathrm{BF}_3 \\text { and } \\mathrm{NO}_2^{-}\\)","\\(\\mathrm{NH}_2^{-}\\) and \\(\\mathrm{H}_2 \\mathrm{O}\\)","\\(\\mathrm{NH}_2^{-}\\) and \\(\\mathrm{BF}_3\\)"],"answer":1,"solution":"$\\begin{aligned} & \\mathrm{BF}_3 \\rightarrow \\mathrm{sp}^2 \\\\ & \\mathrm{NO}_2{ }^{-} \\mathrm{sp}^2 \\\\ & \\mathrm{H}_2 \\mathrm{O} \\rightarrow \\mathrm{sp}^3 \\\\ & \\mathrm{NO}_2 \\rightarrow \\mathrm{sp}^2 \\\\ & \\mathrm{NH}_2{ }^{-} \\rightarrow \\mathrm{sp}^3\\end{aligned}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (09 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":27813,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Chemical Bonding and Molecular Structure","question":"","options":["A - II, B - III, C - IV, D - I","A - IV, B - III, C - II, D - I","A - II, B - I, C - IV, D - III","A - IV, B - I, C - II, D - III"],"answer":1,"solution":"From the following lewis structures of&nbsp;&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>IF</mi><mn>7</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><msubsup><mi>ICl</mi><mn>4</mn><mo>-</mo></msubsup><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><msub><mi>XeF</mi><mn>6</mn></msub><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#38;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><msub><mi>XeF</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math>:<br /><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/71fb8ea8-a496-494d-95d4-1a709cb41a09-17.PNG\" style=\"width: 134px; height: 150px;\" />,&nbsp;<img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/2428e40c-8804-4e82-a8c7-fdb63599c5aa-18.PNG\" style=\"width: 173px; height: 150px;\" />,&nbsp;<img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/aed2004b-6c76-433d-a0aa-f7443277adbd-20.PNG\" style=\"width: 124px; height: 150px;\" />&nbsp;and&nbsp;<img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/dbcfc661-5a32-4bee-bde5-0f30fd7fb402-21.PNG\" style=\"width: 200px; height: 64px;\" /><br />we can deduce the number of lone pairs as well as the hybridisation of the central atom:<br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtable><mtr><mtd><msub><mi>IF</mi><mn>7</mn></msub><mo>:</mo></mtd><mtd><mi>zero</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>lone</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>pair</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mi>sp</mi><mn>3</mn></msup><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mn>3</mn></msup></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><msubsup><mi>ICl</mi><mn>4</mn><mo>-</mo></msubsup><mo>:</mo></mtd><mtd><mi>two</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>lone</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>pair</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mi>sp</mi><mn>3</mn></msup><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><msub><mi>XeF</mi><mn>6</mn></msub><mo>:</mo></mtd><mtd><mi>one</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>lone</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>pair</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mi>sp</mi><mn>3</mn></msup><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><msub><mi>XeF</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>:</mo></mtd><mtd><mi>three</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>lone</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>pair</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mi>sp</mi><mn>3</mn></msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi></mtd></mtr></mtable></math>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (30 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":27751,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Chemical Bonding and Molecular Structure","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/Sxu57yj6I3GaE82dH5N9lMflpl8vURQY403SjvMVyq8.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (08 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":27993,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Chemical Bonding and Molecular Structure","question":"","options":["$\\mathrm{H}_2 \\mathrm{~S} < \\mathrm{SiH}_4 < \\mathrm{NH}_3 < \\mathrm{BF}_3$","$\\mathrm{H}_2 \\mathrm{~S} < \\mathrm{NH}_3 < \\mathrm{BF}_3 < \\mathrm{SiH}_4$","$\\mathrm{H}_2 \\mathrm{~S} < \\mathrm{NH}_3 < \\mathrm{SiH}_4 < \\mathrm{BF}_3$","$\\mathrm{NH}_3 < \\mathrm{H}_2 \\mathrm{~S} < \\mathrm{SiH}_4 < \\mathrm{BF}_3$"],"answer":2,"solution":"$\\mathrm{H}_2 \\mathrm{~S} \\longrightarrow \\mathrm{sp}^3$\n$\\mathrm{NH}_3 \\longrightarrow \\mathrm{sp}^3$\n$\\mathrm{BF}_3 \\longrightarrow \\mathrm{sp}^2$\n$\\mathrm{SiH}_4 \\longrightarrow \\mathrm{sp}^3$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2004","image":null},{"id":27878,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Chemical Bonding and Molecular Structure","question":"","options":["Both Statement <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi></math>&nbsp;and Statement <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>II</mi></math>&nbsp;are false","Statement <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi></math>&nbsp;is true but Statement <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>II</mi></math>&nbsp;is false","Statement <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi></math>&nbsp;is false but Statement <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>II</mi></math>&nbsp;is true","Both Statement <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi></math>&nbsp;and Statement <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>II</mi></math>&nbsp;are true"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/39900c3a-15d7-4117-b854-0eca8f65f3da-image.png\" style=\"width: 113px; height: 116px;\" /></p><p>Intramolecular <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></math>-bonding</p><p>thus it is more volatile due to intramolecular <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></math>-bonding.</p><p>Melting point of o-nitrophenol is higher because of closed packing and not because of hydrogen bonding.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (26 Feb Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":27839,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Chemical Bonding and Molecular Structure","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>0</mn></math> , triangular planar.<br />&nbsp;","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn></math> , pyramidal.<br />&nbsp;","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn></math> , bent <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">T</mi></math>-shape.<br />&nbsp;","&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn></math>, bent <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">T</mi></math>-shape"],"answer":2,"solution":"<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/43095492-e3cf-4cb8-841d-93a31f614c0f-1.png\" style=\"width: 170px; height: 187px;\" /></p><p>Bromine undergo <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>sp</mi><mn>3</mn></msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi></math> hybridization and the shape of the molecule is T-shape. Each fluorine is having <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>3</mn></math> lone pairs and bromine is having <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn></math> lone pairs. Hence, total <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>11</mn></math> lone pairs are there.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (29 Jun Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":27904,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Chemical Bonding and Molecular Structure","question":"","options":["dipole-dipole&nbsp;<math><mo>&#62;</mo></math>&nbsp;ion-dipole&nbsp;<math><mo>&#62;</mo></math> ion-ion","ion-dipole <math><mo>&#62;</mo></math> ion-ion <math><mo>&#62;</mo></math> dipole-dipole","ion-dipole <math><mo>&gt;</mo></math> dipole-dipole <math><mo>&gt;</mo></math> ion-ion","ion-ion <math><mo>&gt;</mo></math> ion-dipole <math><mo>&gt;</mo></math> dipole-dipole"],"answer":3,"solution":"Interionic/intermolecular forces <math><mo>&#8733;</mo></math> charge present on species<br />As ions are charged while dipole is only partially charged so the relative strength of interionic/intermolecular forces in decreasing order is:<br />Ion-Ion <math><mo>&#62;</mo></math>&nbsp;Ion-Dipole <math><mo>&#62;</mo></math>&nbsp;Dipole-Dipole","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2020 (07 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":27872,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Chemical Bonding and Molecular Structure","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>NO</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>Cl</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msubsup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">N</mi><mn>3</mn><mo>-</mo></msubsup></math>"],"answer":3,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/ba28e4e0-a519-43f4-9cf0-a13ae8158a1b-image.png\" style=\"width: 528px; height: 151px;\" />","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (17 Mar Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":27812,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Chemical Bonding and Molecular Structure","question":"","options":["C, D, E only","B, E, A only","A, C, D only","A, B, D only"],"answer":3,"solution":"<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/97abbbcc-77b9-4dc2-a1a8-dce9a9e1fac4-9895313.png\" style=\"width: 400px; height: 288px;\" /></p><ul>\t<li>Two lone pair one oxygen</li>\t<li>Molecule is &#39;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>v</mi></math>&#39; shaped(Due to lone pair)</li>\t<li>Bond angle is less than <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>104</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>&#176;</mo><mfenced><mrow><mn>102</mn><mo>&#176;</mo></mrow></mfenced></math>(Due to lone pair)</li>\t<li><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi><mo>&#183;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">S</mi><mo>&#183;</mo></math> of &#39;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">O</mi></math>&#39; is <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>+</mo><mn>2</mn></math>(Fluorine is more electronegative than oxygen)</li></ul>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (30 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":27740,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Chemical Bonding and Molecular Structure","question":"","options":["\\(\\mathrm{BF}_3 < \\mathrm{PF}_3 < \\mathrm{ClF}_3\\)","\\(\\mathrm{ClF}_3 < \\mathrm{PF}_3 < \\mathrm{BF}_3\\)","\\(\\mathrm{PF}_3 < \\mathrm{BF}_3 < \\mathrm{ClF}_3\\)","\\(\\mathrm{BF}_3=\\mathrm{PF}_3 < \\mathrm{ClF}_3\\)"],"answer":1,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/-zIoG6G02UedQ91wKW1Yvw6SWv_TrsMTjljNEo73nJI.original.fullsize.png\"><br />Order of bond angle is $\\mathrm{ClF}_3 < \\mathrm{PF}_3 < \\mathrm{BF}_3$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (09 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":27779,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Chemical Bonding and Molecular Structure","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>2s and 2p atomic orbitals combine, forming σ (sigma) and π (pi) molecular orbitals. σ orbitals result from head-on overlap, while π orbitals arise from sideways overlap. This molecular orbital theory explains the bonding in molecules</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn></mn></math><mo> </mo><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi></math> orbital will form, two molecular orbitals <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">σ</mi><mn>2</mn><mo> </mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">σ</mi><mo>*</mo><mn>2</mn><mo> </mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi></math>.<br/><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">p</mi></math> orbital will form six molecular orbitals <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">σ</mi><mn>2</mn><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">p</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">z</mi></msub></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">σ</mi><mo>*</mo><mn>2</mn><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">p</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">z</mi></msub></math>. <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">π</mi><mn>2</mn><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">p</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">x</mi></msub><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">π</mi><mn>2</mn><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">p</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">y</mi></msub></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">π</mi><mo>*</mo><mn>2</mn><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">p</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">x</mi></msub><mo>,</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">π</mi><mo>*</mo><mn>2</mn><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">p</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">y</mi></msub></math></p><p>Hence the total number of molecular orbitals formed from <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">p</mi></math> atomic orbitals of a diatomic molecule formed is <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>8</mn></math>.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (30 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":27876,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Chemical Bonding and Molecular Structure","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math> is correct but <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">R</mi></math> is not correct","Both <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">R</mi></math> are correct and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">R</mi></math> is the correct explanation of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math> is not correct but <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">R</mi></math> is correct","Both <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">R</mi></math> are correct but <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">R</mi></math> is <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>NOT</mi></math> the correct explanation of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math>"],"answer":3,"solution":"<p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">T</mi><mi>&#8467;</mi><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#8658;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mfenced><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">T</mi><msup><mi>&#8467;</mi><mo>&#8853;</mo></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#38;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><msubsup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mn>3</mn><mo>&#8861;</mo></msubsup></mrow></mfenced></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>CsI</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#8658;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mfenced><mrow><msup><mi>Cs</mi><mo>&#8853;</mo></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#38;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><msubsup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mn>3</mn><mo>&#8861;</mo></msubsup></mrow></mfenced></math></p><p>[Both have same crystalline structure is called isomorphous]</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">T</mi><msubsup><mi>&#8467;</mi><mfenced><mn>81</mn></mfenced><mo>&#8853;</mo></msubsup><mo>=</mo><mfenced close=\"]\" open=\"[\"><msub><mi>Xe</mi><mn>54</mn></msub></mfenced><mn>4</mn><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">f</mi><mn>14</mn></msup><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mn>10</mn></msup><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mn>6</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></math></p><p>(It is correct due to present <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>14</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">f</mi></math> electrons in <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>T&#8467;</mi><mo>&#8853;</mo></msup></math> ion)</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">T</mi><mi mathvariant=\"script\">l</mi><msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math> is <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">T</mi><msup><mi>&#8467;</mi><mo>+</mo></msup><msubsup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mn>3</mn><mo>-</mo></msubsup></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>CSI</mi><mn>3</mn></msub></math> is <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>Cs</mi><mo>+</mo></msup><msubsup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">I</mi><mn>3</mn><mo>-</mo></msubsup></math></p><p>Thallium shows <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">T</mi><msup><mi>&#8467;</mi><mo>+</mo></msup></math> state due to inert pair effect.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (26 Feb Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":27864,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Chemical Bonding and Molecular Structure","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"Bond order of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>CO</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>3</mn></math><br />Bond order of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>NO</mi><mo>+</mo></msup><mo>=</mo><mn>3</mn></math><br />Difference <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">x</mi><mn>2</mn></mfrac></math><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">x</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></math>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (27 Jul Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":27713,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Chemical Bonding and Molecular Structure","question":"","options":["$\\mathrm{sp}^{2}$ and $\\mathrm{sp}^{3}$","Both $\\mathrm{sp}^{3}$","$\\mathrm{sp}^{3}$ and $\\mathrm{sp}^{2}$","Both $\\mathrm{sp}^{2}$"],"answer":0,"solution":"XF₃ is a Lewis acid, indicating the central atom X lacks a complete octet and can accept electron pairs. This is characteristic of Boron (B).<br>Boron in BF₃:<br>Valence electrons: 3<br>Steric number: 3 (three B-F bonds, no lone pairs)<br>Geometry: Trigonal planar<br>Hybridization: sp²<br>YF₃ is a Lewis base, indicating the central atom Y has lone pair(s) available to donate. This is characteristic of Nitrogen (N).<br>Nitrogen in NF₃:<br>Valence electrons: 5<br>Steric number: 4 (three N-F bonds + one lone pair)<br>Geometry: Trigonal pyramidal<br>Hybridization: sp³<br>Therefore, the hybridizations are sp² for XF₃ (Boron) and sp³ for YF₃ (Nitrogen).","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (22 January Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":27696,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Chemical Bonding and Molecular Structure","question":"","options":["Both Statement I and Statement II are true","Both Statement I and Statement II are false","Statement I is true but Statement II is false","Statement I is false but Statement II is true"],"answer":3,"solution":"Statement I: Number of compounds in which sulphur does not follow the octet rule (from $SO_2$, $SO_3$, $SF_4$, $SF_6$ and $H_2S$).<br><br>$SO_2$: The formal-charge-minimised structure $O=S=O$ places $10$ electrons around sulphur (expanded octet).<br>$SO_3$: With three $S=O$ double bonds, sulphur has $12$ electrons around it (expanded octet).<br>$SF_4$: $4$ bond pairs $+ 1$ lone pair $= 10$ electrons around $S$ (expanded octet).<br>$SF_6$: $6$ bond pairs $= 12$ electrons around $S$ (expanded octet).<br>$H_2S$: $2$ bond pairs $+ 2$ lone pairs $= 8$ electrons around $S$ (obeys the octet rule).<br><br>Depending on whether formal-charge-minimised structures are used for $SO_2$ and $SO_3$, either $2$ ($SF_4, SF_6$) or $4$ ($SO_2, SO_3, SF_4, SF_6$) species violate the octet rule, but the number is never $3$.<br>Hence, Statement I is false.<br><br>Statement II: Among the given sets, exactly one contains only molecules having one lone pair on the central atom.<br><br>Number of lone pairs on the central atom, $\\text{LP} = \\dfrac{\\text{valence electrons of central atom} - \\text{number of bonded monovalent atoms}}{2}$:<br><br>$H_2O$: $\\dfrac{6 - 2}{2} = 2$ lone pairs<br>$ClF_3$: $\\dfrac{7 - 3}{2} = 2$ lone pairs<br>$SF_4$: $\\dfrac{6 - 4}{2} = 1$ lone pair<br>$NH_3$: $\\dfrac{5 - 3}{2} = 1$ lone pair<br>$BrF_5$: $\\dfrac{7 - 5}{2} = 1$ lone pair<br>$XeF_4$: $\\dfrac{8 - 4}{2} = 2$ lone pairs<br><br>Checking the sets:<br>$\\{H_2O\\ (2),\\ ClF_3\\ (2),\\ SF_4\\ (1)\\}$: not all have $1$ lone pair.<br>$\\{NH_3\\ (1),\\ BrF_5\\ (1),\\ SF_4\\ (1)\\}$: all have exactly $1$ lone pair.<br>$\\{BrF_5\\ (1),\\ ClF_3\\ (2),\\ XeF_4\\ (2)\\}$: not all have $1$ lone pair.<br>$\\{XeF_4\\ (2),\\ ClF_3\\ (2),\\ H_2O\\ (2)\\}$: not all have $1$ lone pair.<br><br>Exactly one set satisfies the condition, so Statement II is true.<br><br>Hence, Statement I is false but Statement II is true, which corresponds to option $(4)$.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (06 April Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":27857,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Chemical Bonding and Molecular Structure","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/e494640d-10d0-4e01-a243-c53f1ba4cb7b-image.png\" style=\"width: 542px; height: 123px;\" /></p><p>Hence non-pyramidal species are <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>SO</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>,</mo><msup><msub><mi>NO</mi><mn>3</mn></msub><mo>-</mo></msup></math>and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msubsup><mi>CO</mi><mn>3</mn><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>-</mo></mrow></msubsup></math>.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (27 Aug Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":27918,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Chemical Bonding and Molecular Structure","question":"","options":["A bonding $\\pi$ orbital","A non-bonding orbital","An antibonding $\\sigma$ orbital","An antibonding $\\pi$ orbital"],"answer":3,"solution":"An antibonding $\\pi$ orbital best describes the diagram of a molecular orbital. Two orbitals laterally overlap to form pi bond. Out of phase combination, of these two $p$ orbitals, give $\\pi^*$ MO.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2018 (15 Apr Shift 2 Online)","image":null},{"id":28002,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Chemical Bonding and Molecular Structure","question":"","options":["$\\mathrm{OH}_2$","$\\mathrm{SH}_2$","$\\mathrm{NH}_3$","$\\mathrm{SO}_2$"],"answer":1,"solution":"In $\\mathrm{H}_2 \\mathrm{~S}$, due to low electronegativity of sulphur the L.P. - L.P. repulsion is more than B.P. - B.P. repulsion and hence the bond angle is $92^{\\circ}$.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2003","image":null},{"id":27750,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Chemical Bonding and Molecular Structure","question":"","options":["Statement I is correct but Statement II is incorrect.","Statement I is incorrect but Statement II is correct.","Both Statement I and Statement II are correct.","Both Statement I and Statement II are incorrect."],"answer":0,"solution":"$\\mathrm{N}\\left(\\mathrm{CH}_3\\right)_3$ and $\\mathrm{P}\\left(\\mathrm{CH}_3\\right)_3$ both are Lewis base and acts as ligand, However, $\\mathrm{P}\\left(\\mathrm{CH}_3\\right)_3$ has a $\\pi$-acceptor character.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (08 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":27936,"subject":"Chemistry","chapter":"Chemical Bonding and Molecular Structure","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>SF</mi><mn>6</mn></msub></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>BrF</mi><mn>5</mn></msub></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>PF</mi><mn>5</mn></msub></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mfenced open=\"[\" close=\"]\" separators=\"|\"><msub><mi>CrF</mi><mn>6</mn></msub></mfenced><mrow><mn>3</mn><mo>-</mo></mrow></msup></math>"],"answer":2,"solution":"<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>SF</mi><mn>6</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><msup><mi>sp</mi><mn>3</mn></msup><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></math> <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>BrF</mi><mn>5</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><msup><mi>sp</mi><mn>3</mn></msup><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></math><br /><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mfenced open=\"[\" close=\"]\" separators=\"|\"><msub><mi>CrF</mi><mn>6</mn></msub></mfenced><mrow><mn>3</mn><mo>-</mo></mrow></msup><mo>=</mo><msup><mi>sp</mi><mn>3</mn></msup><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#160;</mi></math> <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>PF</mi><mn>5</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><msup><mi>sp</mi><mn>3</mn></msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi></math>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2017 (08 Apr Online)","image":null}]